HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 597
By Russell
A RESOLUTION to honor Fort Loudoun Electric Cooperative on
the occasion of its eighty-fifth anniversary.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly take great pleasure in recognizing
an organization that has helped bring prosperity and opportunity to the citizens of East
Tennessee for the past eighty-five years; and
WHEREAS, in the 1930s, nine of ten rural farms in Tennessee were without electricity,
and the costs associated with procuring and retaining this life-changing resource were
unbearable for most; and
WHEREAS, concerned citizens living in the rural parts of Blount, Loudon, McMinn,
Meigs, Monroe, and Roane counties came together on August 16 and August 19 of 1940 at the
Madisonville City Hall with a vision to found an electric cooperative in accordance with
legislation passed by the General Assembly in 1935 and 1939; and
WHEREAS, by purchasing some of the electric lines serving Madisonville from the
Tennessee Valley Authority (TVA) and the Tennessee Utilities Company, the Loudon County
Electric Corporation could serve its first members; and
WHEREAS, by the adoption of Articles of Conversion at the Loudon County Courthouse,
the Loudon County Electric Corporation was renamed Fort Loudoun Electric Cooperative
(FLEC) to more accurately represent the region where its potential members lived and worked;
and
WHEREAS, as a private, nonprofit organization owned by its membership, FLEC has
worked with other utilities and the TVA over the years to provide electric service to its members
under a least-cost management philosophy; and
